@@gHISTORY@@W

The oldest fighting discipline in the world belongs not to armies or academies
but to the people who built everything else: cistern laborers who dug the
Keeper Cistern Ring, caravan porters who hauled survey equipment across the
Scorching Sands, bound-service workers at the pyramid construction sites, and
the dispossessed kin displaced when the Ninth Meridian Catastrophe collapsed the
eastern road system. Without weapons, formal backing, or institutional
protection, these groups developed close-quarters disciplines from necessity —
timing, stamina, and body knowledge accumulated across generations of physical
labor and street survival. The pugilist tradition formalizes what they carried.
It is the oldest school because it was never written down, only passed body to
body, and it survived every collapse because it required nothing that could be
seized, registered, or taken away.

@@gPUGILIST@@W

Pugilists are close-quarters specialists who trust stamina, timing, and body
control over steel. They outlast opponents, then punish every opening.

